false, "mention": "PXR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9950159192085266, "span": {"begin": 336, "end": 339}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:948"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cluster of differentiation 36", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9740257263183594, "span": {"begin": 457, "end": 486}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:948"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "platelet glycoprotein 4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9835073947906494, "span": {"begin": 502, "end": 525}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:948"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CD36", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9939039945602417, "span": {"begin": 528, "end": 532}}], "text": "Pregnane X receptor (PXR), also known as steroid NR subfamily 1, group I, member 2 (NR1I2), is a nuclear receptor that can be activated by pregnenolone and progesterone and many chemicals due to low specificity; once activated it binds to Retinoid X receptor (RXR) and increases upregulation of target genes (Mellor et al. 2016). &nbsp;PXR has an important role in lipid homeostasis by regulating the rate of lipid intake particularly through activation of cluster of differentiation 36, also known as platelet glycoprotein 4 [(CD36) (Zhou et al. 2006; Gwag et al. 2019)].", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:25:52 +0000 2026"}